. I argue that the best design is when the user does not notice it. To me, that is the pinnacle of creative in Web design. It is much harder to achieve than bells and whistles. I challenge you to come up with one disadvantage this has for the user.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the thing, next to no one visits your site to check out the design; they are looking for information or are trying to complete some action. If they are not noticing the design, it means it is not getting in their way and conforms to the content. As long as everything is intuitive and the content is easy to find and consume, the look and feel is secondary at best. You could layout the content to make it look like a text file with a menu and search, and no one would care if they can easily get what they came for. Boring yes, but it remains functional and fulfills its purpose. Have you ever paid any attention to the design of Google\'s main page and search results? Or have you seldom noticed it? I\'ll agree that the UI in some Google products is not the best, but their main line - search - is excellent even though it looks boring. I\'ll bet that you use it everyday despite this. And you know why? because it functions exceptionally well, my grandma can use it like a pro, and it gives you what you want. It\'s the very reason Google rose to mind blowing success nearly overnight.\r\n\r\nI\'m not trying to piss anybody off, design is hard and important, but it becomes counter-productive if your number one concern is not the user. No one wants a site that looks boring, humans appreciate visual appeal. As a user, the design of your website is not my main concern when all I want is some particular bit of information. Annoying bells and whistles will catch my attention, just not the kind you are looking for. If the message of your site is not about your creative skills I\'m not on your website to appreciate art. Don\'t overload my senses please.','Creative','','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-v1','','','2017-